Watt and Windy want the next book in a series they're reading, so they head to the library, where a friendly librarian shows them how the library works and how much it has to offer.

5:46 - (Post Office)
Watt and Windy help Carry the mail truck mail a lost letter named Posty. They learn all about how the post office works.

8:31 - (Hospital)
When Watt bumps his bulb at the play park, Frank takes him on his first trip to the hospital. Watt is a little nervous at first, but he soon learns that the hospital is filled with smart doctors and nurses who help him get better. 

11:17 - (Airport)
Watt and his dad are going on a trip to Movieville, so Watt learns all about the airport and the people who work there.

14:02 - (Everywhere I Go)
In an upbeat, country-style song, Carry delivers mail across City Island and explores its many different areas. He identifies these areas as rural, urban, or suburban, and explains what makes each of them unique.

00:00 - (Intro)
Intro.

0:15 - (Shopping)
When Watt accidentally rips the cape of his Superbulb action figure, he goes shopping with Frank and Windy in search of a new one. Along the way, he compares the different kinds of stores and the items they sell.

3:01 - (Maker Hill)
Watt's class travels to Maker Hill, the industrial neighborhood of City Island where goods are made. Watt assumes a wizard uses magic to make everything, but Rosey Rivet shows him that skillful artisans create all of the city's goods.

5:47 - (Swap Day)
Watt attends Swap Day, where he‚Äôs excited to find a Dusty Buster helmet! Unfortunately, the owner is not interested in trading for Watt‚Äôs comic book. Watt learns about relative value, and completes a series of trades to get the helmet. 

8:32 - (Garbage)
When Watt accidentally throws away his dad‚Äôs special pen, they go to the City Island Waste Management Center to find it. Detritus, a grouchy plastic bag, shows them how the city processes waste and helps them track down the missing pen!

11:17 - (Clouds)
City-Henge is the day when the sunset lines up perfectly with Main Street. Watt and Windy travel to Skytown, where Windy‚Äôs family grows  clouds for the event! They learn how the clouds are produced and end the day with a special sunset. 

14:02 - (What is Money?)
Mark outlines the basics of money in a retro 80‚Äôs electronic extravaganza! He explains that money is used to buy goods and services, and that it comes in several different forms and amounts.

5:46 - (Maps)

8:31 - (Flashback)

11:16 - (Internet)
Watt, Mark, and Windy attend an after-school computer club, where they follow an email message on its journey around the world! They learn that the internet is a network of routers and paths that help messages reach their destinations. 

13:30 - (The Media Song)

description:

description:

#PBSKIDS #KeyshawnSolvesIt #Podcast #Juneteenth #mystery #kidsstories  

00:00 - 15:09: Episode 1 - The Birthday Mystery
Keyshawn‚Äôs 10th birthday is full of surprises! His mystery birthday party turns into a real-life mystery.

15:10 - 31:42 Episode 2 - The New Detectives
Keyshawn and Kiki team up to solve the disappearing bike case and find their first clue!

31:43 - 48:27: Episode 3 - Someone‚Äôs Hiding Something 
The more clues that Keyshawn and KiKi discover, the more mysterious their case becomes!

48:28 - 1:03:15: Episode 4 - The Bet
Keyshawn makes a decision that could change everything!

1:03:16 - 1:14:12: Episode 5 - A New Clue
Keyshawn gets one step closer to knowing why bikes are disappearing in his neighborhood.

1:14:23 - 1:24:09: Episode 6 - All Eyes on Keyshawn
Keyshawn is surprised when kids start believing he is the one taking the disappearing bikes!

1:24:10 - 1:38:52: Episode 7 - Finding Facts
Keyshawn and KiKi are ready to use their new detective tool to help solve their case!

1:38:53 - 1:55:03: Episode 8 - Case Solved!
Keyshawn and KiKi race to solve their case!

While playing in their backyard, Nature Cat and his pals become sudden and unexpected contestants on the "on the go" game show "So You Think You Know Nature!" Led by host Twig Stickman, Nature Cat and his friends travel, by the magic of TV game shows, to various exotic locations all around the world to prove that they know nature. description:
Xavier shows up for his very first track and field meet and is dismayed to realize the other kids have had a lot more practice than him. He might never catch up! Wondering if he should just quit now, Yadina and Brad convince him to try something else first‚Ä¶to the Secret Museum! Our heroes are sent back in time to meet an amazing racer: Wilma Rudolph. Though, as our trio soon find out, Wilma wasn‚Äôt always great at running; in fact, she had to wear a leg brace just to walk until she was nine years old. But, Wilma‚Äôs late start didn‚Äôt stop her from becoming an Olympic gold medalist! / Xavier, Yadina and Brad spend the morning shoveling snow off the museum steps so people will be able to visit safely, but are aghast to discover there‚Äôs no hot chocolate reward for all their hard work! What should they do? There‚Äôs only one thing‚Ä¶to the Secret Museum! Our heroes are sent back in time to meet someone who knew about hard work: Jonas Salk. They follow along as Jonas first helps his friends play baseball, then helps millions of kids all around the world by developing a vaccine for polio.  Watching Jonas work hard to accomplish this amazing goal, and expecting nothing in return, helps our trio realize they don‚Äôt need a reward for helping people get to the museum safely, because it feels good to help people.

title: Dinosaur Train FULL EPISODE | Father's Day - Part 1 & Part 2 | PBS KIDS
description:
When the Pteranodon Family visits Troodon Town for a big Father‚Äôs Day celebration, the Conductor sees Mr. Pteranodon enjoying being celebrated, and is compelled to ask his mother whatever happened to his father. She decides that he‚Äôs ready to learn the truth and tells him the story about how his father was the bravest Conductor of them all and dared to build an experimental Drill Train and tunnel into the future -- she believes to the Cenozoic Era, which no dinosaur had ever seen. Unfortunately, the Conductor‚Äôs father never returned, and is apparently lost. The Conductor decides to take the new Drill Train and tunnel into the future to rescue his missing father! SONG: ‚ÄúTHE BRAVEST TROODON‚Äù / The Conductor, determined to find his missing father, takes the experimental Drill Train and drills a new Time Tunnel that goes as far into the end of the Mesozoic Era as possible, to drill farther into the future and find his father, Trevor Troodon. Once Dad and Buddy and Tiny get wind of this plan, they come aboard, too. So they all take the Drill Train and drill into the future. They come out in the Ice Age of the Cenozoic Era, where they meet a huge, furry Mastodon named Maurice. Maurice helps them search through the icy wastes until they find a feather-covered Northern Troodon who turns out to indeed be Trevor, the father of Mr. Conductor! A happy reunion for all, and they bring him home to the Age of Dinosaurs.

#DinosaurTrain #PBSKIDS #FathersDay

description:
Xavier, Yadina and Brad have a lively debate over who the best hero of all time is. Suddenly, whoosh ‚Äì our trio find themselves in the Secret Museum!  They‚Äôre sent back in time to meet someone who truly embodies what it means to be a hero: Harriet Tubman. description:
It's Halloween time and Sid and his friends have dressed up in the spookiest and scariest costumes possible. Sid is a bat with big fangs. May is a spooky black cat. Gabriela is a furry, yucky spider. And Gerald is a super spooky skeleton that goes boo! Susie (dressed as a silly mad scientist) loves their costumes, and helps the kids discover that Halloween can be spooky and scientific! The kids investigate how bats are helpful creatures that catch mosquitoes, spiders are expert engineer web builders, cats are leaping aerial acrobats, and skeletons help hold up our body frames! Susie then ends the day with a special "Halloween Parade" song so the kids can march around and show off their spooky and scientific costumes!

title: Elinor Wonders Why FULL EPISODE | The Town Picnic / The Amazing Expandable Clubhouse | PBS KIDS
description:
"The Amazing Expandable Clubhouse"
Elinor, Olive and Ari are happy to welcome new members to The Explorer's Club, but as more and more kids join, a big problem arises: their clubhouse isn't big enough to fit all the new Explorers! When the entire Clubhouse rolls down the hill, Elinor and her friends need to find a solution. After observing their snail friends, Norma and Lulu, they realize that a snail‚Äôs shell expands as it grows, which gives them the idea to EXPAND their Clubhouse, adding new sections to make it nice and spacious for all to play!

"The Town Picnic"
It's time for the Animal Town picnic, but Ari is growing impatient waiting for Ms. Llama's famous ketchup, which just won‚Äôt come out of the bottle. Meanwhile, Elinor and her friends follow a bee to its hive and observe the honey-making process, where they discover that honey is goopier when it has less water in it. Using this new-found knowledge, the kids are inspired to solve Ms. Llama‚Äôs ketchup problem by adding water and making it less goopy, just in time for Ari to enjoy his delicious sandwich. Yum!

title: Elinor Wonders Why FULL EPISODE | Bird Song / No Need to Shout | PBS KIDS
description:
"Bird Song"
Elinor's Dad is having trouble sleeping in because of the noisy birds outside his window, so Elinor decides to find out why birds sing, and hopefully get her Dad a little peace and quiet. Ari and Olive join her, and the kids come to realize birds sing to communicate, just like how we talk to communicate. The next morning, Elinor uses a whistle to call the bird away so her dad can finally get some sleep. 

"No Need to Shout"
Elinor loses her voice just before she and her friends are supposed to sing their song for the class. She needs to figure out another way to perform, so she and her friends decide to observe nature outside for some ideas. They notice that all sorts of animals use different ways to communicate by using actions instead of words, like a dog wagging its tail vigorously or a baby crying. This gives Elinor the idea that she can act out the actions of the song during their presentation. The show must go on!

title: Elinor Wonders Why FULL EPISODE | The House That Ants Built / Special Places | PBS KIDS
description:
"The House That Ants Built"
Elinor and her friends are trying to make an awesome couch cushion castle, but they each have their own ideas of how to build it. When they can't seem to share materials, it looks like all hope is lost, until Elinor notices ants walking by her windowsill. Fascinated, the kids follow the ants and notice them co-operating with each other to build the perfect nest. Now they know just what to do. The kids go back inside and now that they‚Äôre working together, the castle-building is much smoother. They can even move the biggest pillow ‚Äì together! 

"Special Places"
When Ari can't find his favorite ball, he and his friends retrace his footsteps, where they observe a bird with eggs in her nest, then find Mr. Dog burying a toy. Mr. Dog explains he loves to put things away, which is why he buries them and keeps them safe in their "special place." At that moment, Ari suddenly remembers where he left his ball. Elinor and Olive help him find a "special place" to keep it, AFTER they finish playing, of course!

title: Elinor Wonders Why FULL EPISODE | The Science of Staying Warm / The Seed of an Idea | PBS KIDS
description:
"The Science of Staying Warm"
It‚Äôs a wintery Saturday morning and Elinor, Olive and Ari are getting ready to go out and play in the snow with other kids, but Olive wonders why she has to wear so many winter clothes. This catches Elinor‚Äôs curiosity, so she observes that some kids have thick fur (like her) and others (like Olive) don‚Äôt. At the same time, she sees that the kids with thick fur don‚Äôt need coats, and the ones without thick fur need thicker coats. They conclude that fur must help animals stay warm. Now that Olive understands, she‚Äôs excited to put on her winter stuff and have fun in the snow! 

"The Seed of an Idea"
Elinor becomes fascinated by the Velcro on Ari's new watch and convinces her friends to help her find out how it works. First, they make a list of what Velcro sticks to and what it doesn‚Äôt stick to, but they need more observations, so they head out onto the playground. While outside, they observe that Velcro is very similar to a burr seed that is stuck to Ari‚Äôs shirt, which is no coincidence at all! That‚Äôs when they learn that the invention of Velcro was based off the burr seed. Nature is full of all sorts of inventive ideas!

title: Elinor Wonders Why FULL EPISODE | Backyard Soup / Colorful and Tasty | PBS KIDS
description:
"Backyard Soup"
Elinor loves making ‚ÄúBackyard Soup,‚Äù because all the ingredients come from their backyard garden. She‚Äôs eager to try the same recipe when she visits her grandma and grandpa, but their backyard is a lot different than Elinor's, because they live in the desert. Elinor learns that different plants grow in different environments as she makes a whole different ‚ÄúBackyard Soup‚Äù with her grandparents, where the main ingredient is cactus! 

"Colorful and Tasty"
Elinor and her friends are selling lots of yummy cupcakes, but the problem is no one is buying any. The kids don't understand what's wrong, because everyone loves cupcakes. After observing how flowers attract bees through color and smell, they go back to their bake sale and decorate the table with fantastic colors, and use a fan to spread the aroma of the cupcakes. Before they know it, the place is ‚Äúbuzzing‚Äù and they sell every cupcake!

title: Xavier Riddle and The Secret Museum FULL EPISODE | I am Mary Shelley / I am Harry Houdini | PBS KIDS
description:
"I am Mary Shelley"
Xavier and the gang are excited for a Nature Troop campout, where Xavier has volunteered to tell the first campfire story.  There‚Äôs just one problem: everyone is expecting a spooky story, but Xavier only knows how to tell silly stories.  What‚Äôs he going to do?  He doesn‚Äôt want to disappoint everyone.  To the Secret Museum!  Our heroes are sent back in time to meet an expert spooky storyteller: Mary Shelley.  Mary takes our trio on an imaginative playdate where she spins the leaves and wind into a very spooky tale, which Xavier can‚Äôt help but turn funny.  Is all hope lost??  Mary helps Xavier see that he can tell a story that‚Äôs both spooky AND silly.  The most important thing is to tell stories your own way.

"I am Harry Houdini"
The time has come from Brad to spend his very first night in the museum, and he couldn‚Äôt be more excited.  Except, when the lights go out, Brad realizes it‚Äôs kind of‚Ä¶ gulp‚Ä¶ scary there at night.  Too afraid to stay put in his sleeping bag, there‚Äôs only one thing left to do‚Ä¶ to the Secret Museum!  Our heroes travel back in time to meet someone who knew how to face a scary situation: Harry Houdini.  Harry wants nothing more than to be a brave performer, just like his hero, tightrope walker Fearless Jean.  But, it turns out tightrope walking is scarier than he thought!  Good thing Harry has a trick to help himself, and Brad, make it through to the end: when you‚Äôre scared, take a deep breath to calm down and feel better.

MOLLY OF DENALI follows the adventures of feisty and resourceful 10-year-old Molly Mabray, an Alaska Native girl. Molly helps her mom and dad run the Denali Trading Post, a general store, bunkhouse, and transport hub in the fictional village of Qyah, Alaska.

Harness the science of movement as you learn about the physics of rotation with break-dancers Tori Torsion, B-Girl Eren and B-Boy Evol; make time to dance, twirl, climb, run, jump, or slide with your kids, as these early experiences with forces and motion will ignite their curiosity and provide a foundation for future science study.

WHAT‚ÄôS GOOD, a new, six-part video series designed for parents where inspiration and information meet the power of science. Each episode ventures to a new location to meet people from various backgrounds ‚Äì dancers, poets, musicians, artists, athletes, chefs, conservationists and scientists ‚Äì and connects their knowledge and talents to a simple, real-world lesson in the area of science.

She is the Deputy Project Scientist for the Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer and the Principal Investigator for the NEOWISE project to study minor planets and the proposed Near Earth Object Camera space telescope mission. Her research interests include asteroids, brown dwarfs, planetary atmospheres, debris disks, star formation and the design and construction of new ground- and space-based instrumentation.

To sum it all up in simple terms: Amy Mainzer is smart. And fun! And even has an asteroid named after her: Asteroid (234750) Amymainzer.

Recently, she‚Äôs joined the PBS KIDS family as science consultant and host for the new series, Ready Jet Go! #YouCanBeAnything

description:
Dr. Scott Sampson ‚Äì Dinosaur Paleontologist and Vice President of Research & Collections and Chief Curator at the Denver Museum of Nature & Science
 
Dr. Scott Sampson fell in love with dinosaurs at the age of four.  He was able to spell the word ‚Äúpaleontology‚Äù before he was able to spell his last name.  Since then, Dr. Scott has built a career on researching and studying ancient life and sharing his love of dinosaurs with audiences of all ages.  He currently serves as Vice President of Research and Collections and Chief Curator at the Denver Museum of Nature & Science, and as host and science advisor for the PBS KIDS television series Dinosaur Train. Sampson is also Program Ambassador of Nature Rocks, a global initiative of The Nature Conservancy aimed at inspiring families to explore nature.

title: READY JET GO | Premiering Monday, February 15th on PBS KIDS
description:
A new show from PBS KIDS, Ready Jet Go premieres February 15th!

READY JET GO! takes viewers on a journey into outer space, building on children‚Äôs curiosity about science, technology and astronomy. The series follows two neighborhood kids: Sean, who has an all-consuming drive for science facts, and Sydney, who has a passion for science fiction and imagination. They both befriend the new kid on their street, Jet Propulsion, whose family members happen to be aliens from the planet Bortron 7. Together, they explore the solar system and the effects it has on the science of our planet, while learning about friendship and teamwork along the way.

READY JET GO! features live-action interstitials with Jet Propulsion Laboratory astronomer Dr. Amy Mainzer, who also is the science curriculum consultant for the show. Created by Craig Bartlett, who also created PBS KIDS‚Äô hit series DINOSAUR TRAIN, READY JET GO! is produced by Wind Dancer Films. PBS SoCaL is a station partner for the series.

Squeeks! Kate McKinnon! What could be better? Hear about the "special techniques" Kate uses to voice Squeeks in the new PBS KIDS series -- Nature Cat. Play the video to watch Kate in action, and learn more about #NatureCatPBS here: http://to.pbs.org/naturecatsite

Watch Nature Cat on your local PBS station, or watch anytime, anywhere on the PBS KIDS Video app. Check your local listings here: http://pbskids.org/tv-times/

Through NATURE CAT, co-creators and brothers David Rudman (SESAME STREET, The Muppets) and Adam Rudman (Tom & Jerry, SESAME STREET, CYBERCHASE) have teamed up to inspire viewers to get outdoors and develop connections with the natural world. Designed for kids ages 3-8, the multiplatform media property premieres this fall on PBS KIDS, along with integrated digital content and hands-on activities. Inspired by research on the health and educational benefits of spending time outside, NATURE CAT will encourage families to get active and go on their own outdoor adventures.

title: APPS & GAMES | PBS KIDS ScratchJr
description:
DOWNLOAD APP FOR iTUNES STORE: https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/pbs-kids-scratchjr/id1047840202?mt=8

DOWNLOAD APP FROM GOOGLE PLAY: https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=org.pbskids.scratchjr

PBS KIDS ScratchJr helps children ages 5-8 learn core coding concepts as they create their own interactive stories and games using PBS KIDS characters. PBS KIDS ScratchJr incorporates PBS KIDS media properties, including WILD KRATTS, WORDGIRL, PEG + CAT and the new series NATURE CAT. As kids snap together colorful programming blocks to make their favorite characters move, jump, dance and sing, they will learn to solve problems, design projects and express themselves creatively.

PBS KIDS ScratchJr is now available for free from the App Store on iPad and from Google Play store on Android tablet. More information on PBS KIDS apps is available at pbskids.org/apps 

PBS KIDS ScratchJr is a collaboration between the DevTech Research Group at the Eliot-Pearson Department of Child Study and Human Development in Tufts University‚Äôs School of Arts and Sciences, the Lifelong Kindergarten Group at the MIT Media Lab, and the Playful Invention Company. 

PBS KIDS ScratchJr Features
‚Ä¢ Colorful Programming Blocks: Snap together the color-coded programming blocks to create sequences of actions that cause characters to animate and interact in fun and exciting ways.
‚Ä¢ PBS KIDS Characters and Backgrounds: Create projects based on PBS KIDS shows and mix-and-match over 150 characters.
‚Ä¢ Paint Editing: Create unique characters and backgrounds.
‚Ä¢ Voice Recording: Use the recording tool to add sounds and give voice to projects.
‚Ä¢ Story Starters: Find inspiration with in-app story starters! Each Story Starter features a different set of characters and is designed to encourage children to edit and complete the story however they‚Äôd like

title: KART KINGDOM | Water Moves- KSPS Event | PBS KIDS
description:
Welcome to Kart Kingdom's "Water Moves" day! 

Kids from the Northeast Youth Center worked as a team to earn points at KSPS's Fit Kids Day! 

Have you been to Kart Kingdom? It‚Äôs a world of adventure waiting to be discovered, and crazy things are happening in the Kart Kingdom blog! Visit the blog for prizes and secret codes that unlock new karts. Check out the new free game just for kids by PBS KIDS.

Play Kart Kingdom at http://to.pbs.org/kidskartkingdom

Kart Kingdom is based on the system thinking curriculum. Any curriculum and educational resources for Kart Kingdom is developed with the help of our educational advisor, Arizona State University‚Äôs Center for Games and Impact.

Kart Kingdom helps players understand systems. A system refers to several different things that work together to create a whole, such as the pipes in the water system. Without the pipes, water cannot travel from the dam to your faucet at home. The idea of systems thinking is for an individual to understand what the system is and how it works. To be able to process using systems thinking is a crucial life skill for scientists, engineers, etc.

Kart Kingdom is based on the system thinking curriculum. Any curriculum and educational resources for Kart Kingdom is developed with the help of our educational advisor, Arizona State University‚Äôs Center for Games and Impact.

Kart Kingdom helps players understand systems. A system refers to several different things that work together to create a whole, such as the pipes in the water system. title: GAME | PLAY KART KINGDOM | PBS KIDS
description:
Customize your own kart, create your own adventure, and explore new worlds in Kart Kingdom ‚Äì a new free game just for kids by PBS KIDS.

Play Kart Kingdom at http://to.pbs.org/kidskartkingdom

Kart Kingdom is based on the system thinking curriculum. Any curriculum and educational resources for Kart Kingdom is developed with the help of our educational advisor, Arizona State University‚Äôs Center for Games and Impact.

Kart Kingdom helps players understand systems. A system refers to several different things that work together to create a whole, such as the pipes in the water system. Without the pipes, water cannot travel from the dam to your faucet at home. The idea of systems thinking is for an individual to understand what the system is and how it works. To be able to process using systems thinking is a crucial life skill for scientists, engineers, etc.

title: APP | Peg + Cat Tree Problem | PBS KIDS
description:

Based on the Emmy Award-winning PBS KIDS series PEG + CAT, The Tree Problem offers a series of games designed to encourage children to engage in creative problem solving and Tree alert! Cat is stuck in a tree and he needs your help to get down! Based on the Emmy Award-winning PBS KIDS series PEG + CAT, The Tree Problem offers a series of games designed to encourage children to engage in creative problem solving and practice early math skills.

Download the app at http://pbskids.org/apps/peg--cat-tree-problem.html

Features:
‚Ä¢50 total levels ‚Äì Cat sure has a knack for getting stuck in trees! Levels of increasing challenge motivate children to practice key early math concepts and skills.
‚Ä¢10 worlds ‚Äì Arrange meteors in space, create bamboo bridges in the forest, line up monkeys at the circus, grow plants on the farm, roll and stack snowballs at the South Pole, arrange set pieces on Broadway and much more! Each world presents 5 new levels, offering children a variety of opportunities to solve the problem.
‚Ä¢Peg and Cat‚Äôs spirited and playful antics engage children in learning foundational math concepts like spatial reasoning and measurement, practicing persistence, and having a totally awesome time doing it!

Peg + Cat: The Tree Problem is based on the PBS KIDS series PEG + CAT, created by Jennifer Oxley and Billy Aronson and produced by The Fred Rogers Company. Made for kids ages 3-6, the app is designed to extend the series‚Äô preschool mathematics curriculum.

title: APP | Odd Squad Blob Chase | PBS KIDS
description:
Something very odd has happened in Odd Squad, the PBS KIDS hit series. A big blue blob has escaped in headquarters ‚Äì and we need your help to get it back into its container!

Blob Chase makes basic math concepts fun for kids (5-8) to learn and practice. In the world of Odd Squad, blobs love nothing more than escaping from their containers. In this game, kids help to recover the blobs by using gadgets to add, subtract, halve or double passageways throughout Odd Squad headquarters.

To discover which gadget works best for each particular challenge, kids problem-solve using:
addition
subtraction
multiplication
division
In Blob Chase, kids use math skills throughout each of the 60 levels to get blobs across bridges, over walls, through tubes and eventually, back into their containers. Happy blobbing!

For more apps from PBS KIDS, visit http://to.pbs.org/kids_appstore.

For more fun with Odd Squad, visit pbskids.org/oddsquad.

title: OH NOAH | Learn Spanish with Oh Noah! | PBS KIDS
description:
Oh Noah! is designed to teach Spanish to children ages six to eight through animated videos with embedded games that help build vocabulary. In each three-minute video, a misunderstanding launches a comic misadventure. Kids learn language better when they can put it into meaningful context. Although, like Noah, they may not understand all the Spanish dialogue, kids can comprehend the story told through rich visual storytelling, much like a silent movie.
